\hypertarget{close-reading}{%
\section{Close Reading}\label{close-reading}}

\definition{Close Reading}{Unpacking the meaning of individual words and phrases in a text.}

\hypertarget{goals}{%
\subsection{Goals}\label{goals}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Unpacking the meaning of individual words and phrases in a text
\item
  Consider effects of author's writers

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    W.r.t. the reader's experience
  \item
    W.r.t. the authors too
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Connecting a part =\textgreater{} Whole

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Looking for connections
  \item
    Look for implications
  \item
    Look for how a text changes in its contexts ``Marian's text w.r.t.
    Beigin nationalism''
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Also, a creative effort!
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{framework}{%
\subsection{Framework}\label{framework}}

\#important One way of close reading is to use the following framework:

\definition[Where X is a literary technique, and Y a theme or a broader point]{Close Reading Framework}{The Author uses X to do Y}

When annotating, look for\ldots{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Repetition
\item
  Irony
\item
  Metaphores
\end{itemize}

etc. But, remember that \emph{this is only the X.} It is not enough to
find a device, but you need to analyze \emph{why} its there.

